using QBEngineer.Core.Entities;
using QBEngineer.Core.Enums;
using QBEngineer.Data.Context;

using Serilog;

namespace QBEngineer.Api.Data.TrainingContent;

public class QualityTraining : TrainingContentBase
{
    public QualityTraining(AppDbContext db, Dictionary<string, int> slugMap) : base(db, slugMap) { }

    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Quality Overview",
            Slug = "quality-overview",
            Summary = "What the Quality module does: QC templates, inspections, lot tracking, SPC, NCRs, CAPAs, ECOs, and gages — and how quality connects to jobs, parts, and production.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/quality"]""",
            Tags = """["quality","qc","inspection","lot","spc","ncr","capa","eco","gage"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Quality Overview\n\nThe Quality module is your central hub for quality control and assurance across the entire manufacturing process. It brings together inspections, lot traceability, statistical process control (SPC), non-conformance reports (NCRs), corrective/preventive actions (CAPAs), engineering change orders (ECOs), and gage management — all in one place.\n\n### QC Templates\n\nTemplates define reusable checklists of inspection checks. Each template has a name, optional description, and an optional link to a specific part. Templates contain checklist items — each item has a description, an optional specification (the expected value or tolerance), a sort order, and a required flag. When you create an inspection, you can select a template and the checklist items pre-populate the inspection.\n\n### QC Inspections\n\nInspections are the core quality records. Each inspection is linked to an inspector (the person performing the check) and can optionally reference a job, a production run, a QC template, and a lot number. Inspections track their status — In Progress, Passed, or Failed — and contain individual inspection results. Each result records the check description, whether it passed, the measured value, and notes. The results summary column shows how many checks passed out of the total (e.g., 5/6).\n\n### Lot Tracking\n\nThe Lots tab tracks material lot records for traceability. Each lot has a unique lot number, is linked to a part, and records quantity, optional job reference, supplier lot number, expiration date, and notes. The traceability feature lets you click any lot and see every linked record: jobs that used this lot, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations where the material is stored, and QC inspections performed against it. This is critical for recall management and regulatory compliance.\n\n### SPC (Statistical Process Control)\n\nSPC provides real-time process monitoring through three sub-tabs:\n- **SPC Charts** — X-bar and Range control charts for any measured characteristic. Shows control limits (UCL, LCL, center line), spec limits (USL, LSL), and flags out-of-control points.\n- **SPC Data Entry** — Record measurement subgroups for a selected characteristic. Each subgroup contains multiple readings; the system calculates mean, range, standard deviation, and detects OOC conditions automatically.\n- **OOC Events** — Lists all out-of-control events with severity (Warning, Out of Control, Out of Spec), acknowledgment tracking, and the ability to create a CAPA directly from an OOC event.\n\nSPC characteristics are defined per part and optionally per operation. Each characteristic specifies nominal value, upper/lower spec limits, sample size, measurement type (variable or attribute), unit of measure, decimal places, and gage reference. Process capability indices (Cp, Cpk, Pp, Ppk) are calculated automatically.\n\n### NCRs (Non-Conformance Reports)\n\nNCRs document quality failures. Each NCR has a unique NCR number, type (Internal, Supplier, or Customer), and is linked to a part. NCRs track the detection stage (Receiving, In Process, Final Inspection, Shipping, Customer, Audit), affected and defective quantities, containment actions, and disposition (Use As Is, Rework, Scrap, Return to Vendor, Sort & Screen, Concession). NCRs flow through statuses: Open, Under Review, Contained, Dispositioned, Closed. Material and labor cost impact are tracked for Cost of Poor Quality (COPQ) analysis. NCRs can link to jobs, production runs, lots, sales orders, purchase orders, QC inspections, customers, and vendors.\n\n### CAPAs (Corrective and Preventive Actions)\n\nCAPAs drive systematic problem resolution. Each CAPA has a number, type (Corrective or Preventive), source type (NCR, Audit, Customer Complaint, OOC Event, Internal, Supplier), and goes through phases: Identification, Containment, Root Cause Analysis, Corrective Action, Verification, Effectiveness Check. Root cause methods include 5 Whys, Fishbone Diagram, Fault Tree, and 8D. CAPAs track tasks, owner assignment, priority, due dates, and effectiveness verification with a scheduled check date.\n\n### ECOs (Engineering Change Orders)\n\nECOs manage controlled changes to parts, processes, and documentation. Each ECO has a number, title, description, change type (New, Revision, Obsolescence, Cost Reduction, Quality Improvement), priority (Low, Normal, High, Critical), and flows through statuses: Draft, Review, Approved, In Implementation, Implemented, Cancelled. ECOs track affected items (parts, BOMs, operations) with old/new values and implementation status.\n\n### Gages\n\nThe Gages tab manages measurement instruments and their calibration lifecycle. Each gage has a number, description, type, manufacturer, model, serial number, and accuracy/range/resolution specifications. Gages track calibration interval (in days), last calibration date, and next calibration due date. Statuses include In Service, Due for Calibration, Out for Calibration, Out of Service, and Retired. Each gage maintains a history of calibration records with result (Pass, Fail, Adjusted, Out of Tolerance), lab name, certificate file, standards used, and as-found/as-left conditions.\n\n### How Quality Connects to Other Features\n\n**Jobs:** Inspections link to jobs so you can see all quality checks performed for a specific job. NCRs reference the job where the defect was found.\n\n**Parts:** Templates and SPC characteristics are defined per part. NCRs identify the defective part. Lot records trace material back to specific parts.\n\n**Lots:** Lot numbers thread through inspections, production runs, purchase orders, and bin locations — providing full material traceability from receipt to shipment.\n\n**Scanner Integration:** The quality page responds to barcode scans. On the Inspections tab, a scan fills the search field. On the Lots tab, a scan fills the lot search field. This enables quick lookup of parts or lots on the shop floor.\n\n### When to Use Quality\n\n- When performing incoming, in-process, or final inspections\n- When tracking material lots for traceability and recall readiness\n- When monitoring process stability with SPC charts\n- When documenting non-conformances and driving corrective actions\n- When managing engineering changes to parts or processes\n- When tracking gage calibration schedules and records","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
